                   Installing Billing

 Get sources

 Change directory to src/bee
	cd src/bee
 Make & install binaries, by: 
	make libs all install
 Make directory /var/bee
	mkdir /var/bee
 Make empty files accounts.dat & beelog.dat by:
	cd /var/bee
	touch accounts.dat
	touch beelog.dat
 Make & edit file /var/bee/reslinks.cfg. For example:
  If your network have following users:

  acc	mail			host
  0      boss@pupkin.com	192.168.1.100
  1	peter@pupkin.com	192.168.1.106
  2	 mary@pupkin.com	192.168.1.107
				192.168.1.108 (Mary has two computers)
  3	barbi@pupkin.com	192.168.1.30
  4	  ken@pupkin.com	192.168.1.31

 Your reslinks.cfg will be:

# (comments in reslinks.cfg)
	inet	0	0	192.168.1.100/32
	inet	1	1	192.168.1.106/32
	inet	2	2	192.168.1.107/32
	inet	3	2	192.168.1.108/32
	inet	4	3	192.168.1.30/32
	inet	5	4	192.168.1.31/32

	mail	0	0	boss@pupkin.com
	mail	1	1	peter@pupkin.com
	mail	2	2	mary@pupkin.com
	mail	3	3	barbi@pupkin.com
	mail	4	4	ken@pupkin.com

	adder	0	0	boss
	adder	1	1	peter
	adder	2	2	mary
	adder	3	3	barbi
	adder	4	4	ken

 Run billing console & add new accounts:

	# bee -c
	100 Billing version 0.0.1.0
	100 loading resource links ...
	000 Ready
	new
	000 account 0 added
	new
	000 account 1 added
	new
	000 account 2 added
	new
	000 account 3 added
	new
	000 account 4 added
	exit
	100 Have a nice day
	#

 Edit IPF rules 
  * limit access to billing port (49160 by default)
  * make sure, that only billing will be pass users to inet
  * add line "#<beerules>" for billing

 Add "/usr/local/bin/bee -d -u" line to /etc/rc.local file

 Edit "/usr/local/bin/beetraff-ipf.sh" to meet your needs

 Add "/usr/local/bin/beetraff-ipf.sh" to crontab (to run every 5 minutes)


 I guess it's all.   